Files in this directory
=======================

core:
    The actual core dump.

threads:
    Contains information about the threads in the process. It shows
    the name of the thread (which can not be stored in the core), as
    well as the thread id as seen in gdb and the pid in the host
    and the process namespaces.

pre:
    A directory with files collected from /proc before the process
    was stopped. As stopping the process means that all kernel threads
    are pulled out of their syscall, we can't grab the kernel stack
    during freeze. So we collect it beforehand, accepting the risk
    that the thread might have changed state in the meantime. It might
    still be useful in some cases.

proc:
    Files pulled from /proc during the freeze. The main purpose is to
    save the state of the file descriptors with the corresponding socket
    states. Additional files the might be useful are added.

netlink_*.raw:
    Raw netlink dumps as received from the netlink socket. These
    complement the information from /proc/pid/net, as they contain
    more information.
    A dumper has yet to be provided.

root:
    Only present when requested with -b.
    Main executable and shared libraries of the process. These can be
    useful for standalone analysis.
    To use this with gdb, invoke gdb with
      gdb core.xxx/exe
        set sysroot /path/to/core.xxx/root
        set auto-load safe-path /path/to/core.xxx/root
        core core.xxx/core
    Only issue the auto-load command if you trust the target
    libthread_db.so. Absolute paths are required for libthread_db.so
    to work.

exe:
    Only present when requested with -b.
    Symlink to the main executable. See above.
